WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.120
Hello everyone, welcome to episode 3 of the Grand Prixquel Podcast, where we discuss all things feeder series.

00:06.120 --> 00:10.660
On today's episode, we are going to be doing a Formula 3 season preview.

00:10.660 --> 00:15.620
Our hosts today are myself, Robin, Alex, Peter, and Nova.

00:15.620 --> 00:20.070
And shout out to our producer, Evan, who is here but is not speaking.

00:20.070 --> 00:28.320
I think we should start in team order, so we can start with Campos.

00:28.460 --> 00:34.780
Yeah, so, of course, within Campos, the main kind of driver will be Ugo Ugochukwu.

00:34.780 --> 00:38.560
He won the Formula Regional Oceania Trophy over the winter.

00:38.560 --> 00:48.620
And while he did struggle a bit in F3 last year, he definitely did pick up the results towards the end of the season, I'd say, from around Austria.

00:48.620 --> 00:51.200
Yeah, he was with Prema last year, wasn't he?

00:51.200 --> 00:51.800
Yeah.

00:51.800 --> 00:55.120
Yeah, and obviously we kind of know what's going on with Prema.

00:55.480 --> 00:55.920
Yeah.

00:55.920 --> 01:00.620
But, like, remember when they took the paint off his car last year when they went to the black livery?

01:00.620 --> 01:01.220
Yeah.

01:01.220 --> 01:06.230
He seems like something changed in him, and he definitely did improve as a driver then.

01:06.230 --> 01:13.180
So, the main thing, I think, for him is, can he continue this momentum on, you know, I'd say he finished the season quite strong.

01:13.180 --> 01:15.140
He won in New Zealand.

01:15.880 --> 01:19.400
Can he bring that momentum now to the main F3 season?

01:19.400 --> 01:22.600
I think he definitely could be a title challenger.

01:22.600 --> 01:26.800
But, um, I guess it'll depend on how strong Trident is.

01:26.800 --> 01:30.300
Yeah, but, I mean, Campos were quite strong as well.

01:30.300 --> 01:32.260
I mean, they won the team's title.

01:32.260 --> 01:40.080
And Tsolov was, I mean, until the disqualification in Austria, he was keeping close-ish, I'd say.

01:40.220 --> 01:41.820
Yeah, he was really close.

01:41.820 --> 01:43.340
He was keeping up.

01:43.340 --> 01:46.360
And so, I think Campos can deliver the car.

01:46.360 --> 01:48.860
It's more if Ugo can keep it consistent.

01:48.860 --> 01:52.680
Because, I mean, in Formula Regional Oceania, this isn't true.

01:52.680 --> 01:56.300
But I feel like at other parts of his career, he has struggled with consistency.

01:56.300 --> 02:01.600
And, of course, in New Zealand, it is only one month long, which is a very short season.

02:01.600 --> 02:03.840
Yeah, it was like five weeks in a row, wasn't it?

02:03.840 --> 02:05.360
Was it four or five weeks in a row?

02:05.360 --> 02:06.100
Four weeks.

02:06.100 --> 02:07.240
Four weeks in a row.

02:07.240 --> 02:09.060
And, yeah.

02:09.060 --> 02:14.410
And I feel like we can't ignore the other two drivers in Campos as well, because they are decent.

02:14.410 --> 02:19.000
I mean, yeah, you have Niall, who literally won the Macau Grand Prix in November.

02:19.470 --> 02:26.300
I think we're really, really underrating him, because last season he was with Van Amersfoort, who really did not look really comfortable.

02:26.300 --> 02:31.680
And I remember him, because he was kind of getting that idea of he was really aggressive.

02:31.680 --> 02:37.910
And he was, I don't even know if that's true, but from the German commentators, who often got that title, like he was really aggressive.

02:37.910 --> 02:39.740
And he often got into duels.

02:39.740 --> 02:41.940
But I think he was really interesting.

02:41.940 --> 02:45.840
And I remember him on quite a few occasions where he did really good.

02:45.840 --> 02:56.480
And if Campos can deliver the same package that they also brought to Tsolov and also Boya and Inthraphuvasak, I think it should work out.

02:56.480 --> 03:10.480
And I remember last season where Boya suddenly did, I think it was after he was announced with Aston Martin, where he suddenly seemed to, like, make a huge jump in what he did.

03:10.580 --> 03:16.200
And I wonder if that was exclusively just, you know, his Aston Martin thing.

03:16.200 --> 03:18.800
Or if maybe something else at the team worked.

03:18.800 --> 03:24.360
The same way you talked about Ugo getting better at Prema when they took off the paint.

03:24.360 --> 03:28.200
Maybe Campos found a way to, you know, set up the car better.

03:28.200 --> 03:31.780
Because I also think Tasanapol did really good to it.

03:31.780 --> 03:34.180
Didn't he win the last race or something?

03:34.180 --> 03:37.940
Yeah, he won at some point at the end, I think.

03:38.180 --> 03:40.160
And sometimes I think it's also just a mental thing.

03:40.160 --> 03:46.640
Because, you know, you get, maybe you join an academy or something changes and you finally think mentally, okay, I can do this.

03:46.640 --> 03:51.040
Because the mentality is so important as to how you think of yourself as a driver.

03:51.040 --> 03:52.740
Just mentality speaking.

03:52.740 --> 03:57.540
I mean, as you've said, Ugo Ugochukwu just already won a championship this season.

03:57.540 --> 03:59.240
Nael just won Macau.

03:59.240 --> 04:01.360
Just, like, pretty much last season.

04:02.200 --> 04:04.120
Can someone say something about Rivera?

04:04.120 --> 04:07.800
I mean, hopefully he gets better soon.

04:07.800 --> 04:11.240
Yeah, he got injured in Formula Regional Oceania.

04:11.240 --> 04:18.080
And he hasn't been able to do testing and he's not able to do Australia either.

04:18.080 --> 04:24.000
Yeah, I mean, last year he competed in EC3 and he finished fourth, I think.

04:24.000 --> 04:24.920
So, I mean…

04:24.920 --> 04:30.140
Maybe his big idol is just Carlos Sainz and he'll come back better than ever.

04:30.140 --> 04:31.040
Do we know that?

04:31.040 --> 04:32.220
We have to be positive.

04:32.220 --> 04:35.740
Yeah, no, I mean, it's just more about how serious is his injury.

04:35.740 --> 04:38.360
I think it's his back which he injured, so…

04:38.360 --> 04:39.180
Oh, that's bad.

04:39.180 --> 04:39.600
Yeah.

04:39.600 --> 04:40.020
Yeah.

04:40.020 --> 04:41.920
I just really hope he's good.

04:41.920 --> 04:43.260
It's just, you know…

04:43.260 --> 04:44.890
He doesn't feel like driving.

04:44.890 --> 04:48.700
Obviously, everyone wants to drive, but, like, if it's, like, just a small injury and he's

04:48.700 --> 04:54.770
like, I want to do good over the whole season rather than risk a bigger injury if I get

04:54.770 --> 04:55.950
it back in the car too soon.

04:55.950 --> 05:00.120
Because I think F3 has quite the break before they go on again now.

05:00.120 --> 05:01.740
Yeah, there's, like, a huge break.

05:01.740 --> 05:07.980
Yeah, if you say maybe you only need a week or two or maybe he's good already, but he hasn't

05:07.980 --> 05:13.330
had the chance to train yet again and get back to the feeling in the car, I think it's

05:13.330 --> 05:19.860
better to be careful and then do the rest of the season rather than do one race and risk

05:19.860 --> 05:23.700
not being able to compete any more races over that season.

05:23.700 --> 05:25.420
And I want to be positive for him.

05:25.420 --> 05:27.080
You want to be 100% okay.

05:27.080 --> 05:28.580
You don't want to risk a further injury.

05:28.580 --> 05:32.420
And, yeah, I just wish all the best to him and that he's able to recover.

05:32.420 --> 05:36.700
I don't actually know how to say the name of the guy who's replacing him.

05:36.700 --> 05:39.140
Patrick Heuzenroeder.

05:39.140 --> 05:40.160
Heuzenroeder?

05:40.160 --> 05:40.700
Okay, yeah.

05:40.700 --> 05:42.320
He’s in 

05:42.320 --> 05:43.940
Eurocup 3 with Campos.

05:43.940 --> 05:46.540
He has that home race mentality.

05:46.540 --> 05:47.440
He'll win.

05:47.440 --> 05:48.380
Yeah, exactly.

05:48.380 --> 05:50.560
He'll win it on his debut.

05:50.560 --> 05:53.300
I mean, he did well in GB3 last year.

05:53.300 --> 05:53.820
Yeah.

05:53.820 --> 05:56.080
I mean, he is a solid driver and…

05:56.080 --> 05:58.460
He was runner-up in GB3 last year.

05:58.580 --> 05:59.180
So…

05:59.180 --> 06:01.300
Yeah, so it's more now like…

06:01.300 --> 06:03.800
I mean, of course he'll improve himself and he will...

06:03.800 --> 06:05.860
And Campos is a good team as we've established.

06:05.860 --> 06:08.420
So let's see what he can do next week.

06:08.420 --> 06:12.560
Does anyone else have much to say about Campos or...?

06:12.560 --> 06:15.940
I think one last thing we can say about Ugo is that…

06:15.940 --> 06:18.260
Obviously, he's been dropped by McLaren.

06:19.620 --> 06:21.460
Will that make him drop?

06:21.460 --> 06:22.560
Yeah.

06:22.560 --> 06:31.920
Because I think if we talk about the McLaren Academy, we have to consider the same way that they've just, you know, handled all the juniors.

06:31.920 --> 06:43.080
And I could imagine, especially for him as an American, that maybe there are better possibilities for him if he's not related to McLaren anymore, you know?

06:43.080 --> 06:44.680
The same way that…

06:44.680 --> 06:48.780
I know it's not the same as for Dunne because he actually is closer there.

06:48.780 --> 06:51.360
But for Ugo, it's kind of the same if you think about it.

06:51.360 --> 06:54.780
He's hopefully going to F2 after this season.

06:54.780 --> 06:58.920
And he will not plan to do two seasons in F2.

06:58.920 --> 07:01.480
Yeah, I think if I'm Ugo, I'm very much thinking…

07:01.480 --> 07:02.880
I'd call up Cadillac.

07:03.040 --> 07:03.440
Exactly.

07:03.440 --> 07:05.620
And I'm thinking, OK, I have him to prove now.

07:05.620 --> 07:11.100
Let me go win F3 and prove to these teams how good I am and get them to sign me.

07:11.100 --> 07:11.860
Exactly.

07:11.860 --> 07:19.140
And I think he doesn't necessarily need the monetary support of McLaren.

07:19.140 --> 07:21.640
And I think he can afford racing.

07:21.640 --> 07:22.740
I mean, he's still at Campos.

07:22.740 --> 07:24.160
Campos is still a good team.

07:24.160 --> 07:27.220
Arguably better than Prema was last season.

07:27.780 --> 07:35.420
So I think if I was him and I didn't need McLaren and, you know, you're not promised a seat at McLaren, I would too leave.

07:35.420 --> 07:38.580
Yeah, and yeah, now…

07:38.580 --> 07:39.640
Moving on to Trident.

07:39.640 --> 07:44.040
Yeah, so of course the big name there is Freddie Slater.

07:44.040 --> 07:47.780
If you know me, you know I am one of his biggest fans.

07:47.780 --> 07:51.360
So yeah, he is definitely one of the titles favorites, I'd say.

07:51.560 --> 08:00.280
He won FRECA last year, won Italian F4 the year before, and the year before that he won Ginetta Juniors and KZ2.

08:00.280 --> 08:05.240
So he is fast in everything he competes in.

08:05.240 --> 08:12.720
And of course he had the 2 one-off of F3 appearances last year, taking P2 in the AIX in Bahrain.

08:12.940 --> 08:21.860
So he is very much, I'd say, he's going to come out swinging, and even in testing, he had the fastest time of the test, and he was consistently up there.

08:21.860 --> 08:33.280
So, and given how strong Trident has been the last few years, of course, taking the last, I think, the last three champions to the title, he is totally going to be in the title fight.

08:33.280 --> 08:35.580
I think he's by far the title favorite.

08:35.580 --> 08:36.910
Oh yeah, definitely.

08:37.380 --> 08:39.640
If he's not winning, it's going to be embarrassing.

08:39.640 --> 08:41.200
I'm going to be honest with you.

08:41.200 --> 08:46.940
You know, I respect him, but he's pretty much always been with the strongest, or one of the strongest teams.

08:46.940 --> 08:57.280
And that's nothing to disrespect, but I just want to point out that he has quite a few opportunities that quite a few other drivers do not get.

08:57.280 --> 08:59.340
And, I mean, it's good for him.

08:59.340 --> 09:04.140
If I was super f****ing rich, and I was also good at driving, I'd also drive with the fastest teams.

09:04.320 --> 09:09.580
But if he doesn't win, that would be actually, like, career suicide.

09:09.580 --> 09:16.640
Because he's in, we've said it, like, I think the last three champions were Trident, and always with quite a margin.

09:16.640 --> 09:19.520
I think we saw it with Camara last season.

09:19.520 --> 09:22.340
Yeah, Camara, Fornaroli, Bortoleto.

09:22.340 --> 09:24.340
I mean, we saw it with Camara last season, right?

09:24.340 --> 09:29.410
Where, you know, you just felt like Trident was pretty much already an F2 car.

09:29.410 --> 09:37.910
And I think Slater's really good, but he has not done as many reverse grid races.

09:37.910 --> 09:50.760
So I think that would really be something for me, that either he will prove himself, and if he, like, goes into this weekend, and he goes pole and starts 12th in the reverse grid race,

09:50.790 --> 09:55.500
and he still wins the sprint, you know, then I say, you know what, let's f***ing go.

09:55.500 --> 10:01.760
I mean, I remember at Spa GB3 last year, he had engine issues in qualifying, so he had to start from the back.

10:01.760 --> 10:05.720
And in all three races, he came to finish in, like, the top 10.

10:06.220 --> 10:15.410
But I feel like the top 10 is really difficult, because if you start last in GB3, that's like, you start next to Bianca Bustamante.

10:15.410 --> 10:21.140
So, like, is it really, is it really proof of talent if you can overtake her quickly?

10:21.760 --> 10:33.280
Yeah, but I mean, he went through the whole field quickly, and in the last race, okay, albeit there was a thing with the, I mean, that's the main thing with reverse grid, but that would be an interesting thing.

10:33.280 --> 10:37.400
But I think he does have the racecraft to be able to come through.

10:37.400 --> 10:53.040
I'm just trying to point out that I feel like the midfield of F3 is probably, not a midfield, like, the top 10 that will be lined up on the grid will be stronger than, like, the midfield of GB3.

10:53.040 --> 10:53.980
That's just…

10:53.980 --> 10:54.980
Oh, yeah, definitely.

10:54.980 --> 10:59.940
I think, I mean, of course, in Formula Regional Oceania, there was some reverse grid races and.

10:59.940 --> 11:06.900
Also, the cars are more difficult to use to do a takeover, overtake, what?

11:07.400 --> 11:14.660
Yeah, but he is all by far the favourite for the title, but he does have decent teammates as well.

11:14.660 --> 11:21.580
I mean, de Palo, now signed by McLaren, he was runner-up in FRECA behind Slater last year.

11:21.580 --> 11:31.140
And Stromstead is one of the very many Mercedes academy casualties, so maybe he has something to prove.

11:31.140 --> 11:36.640
Maybe he'll, I don't know, fight Slater for the title or something.

11:36.960 --> 11:42.220
And he was in Trident last year, and he did, you know, he did decent-ish?

11:42.220 --> 11:43.760
Yeah, he was decent last year.

11:43.760 --> 11:45.460
Was he in Trident?

11:45.460 --> 11:46.420
Yeah.

11:46.420 --> 11:47.120
Yeah, he was.

11:47.120 --> 11:49.400
Oh my god, I have to check. I have to check.

11:49.400 --> 11:53.620
Yeah no, he was with Trident, I'm fairly sure.

11:53.620 --> 11:54.760
Yeah, he was.

11:55.220 --> 11:58.460
Was he? Because I did not feel like he was, but maybe he was.

11:58.460 --> 12:00.400
I have to look at it.

12:00.400 --> 12:02.260
Oh my god, he really was.

12:02.260 --> 12:03.760
Wasn't he the weakest out of the bunch?

12:03.760 --> 12:09.380
Which is not bad, because Camara still won the title, and Wurz also did pretty well.

12:10.580 --> 12:21.180
But I saw someone say on Twitter that this Trident lineup is probably the strongest lineup Trident has had in any championship ever.

12:21.180 --> 12:22.780
And you know what? I agree.

12:23.420 --> 12:26.040
Because Slater alone is really, really strong.

12:26.040 --> 12:32.320
But also, de Palo, as you've said, he became runner-up in Freca, which is quite the feat.

12:32.660 --> 12:41.320
And I do not have in mind who actually competed in FRECA last season, but I swear it was a fairly strong grid, I'd say.

12:41.320 --> 12:43.680
It was a pretty good grid, I think.

12:43.680 --> 12:54.300
I feel like what I remember most from last season is that, obviously, you always have the problem of certain teams being stronger, certain teams being weaker, so it's not always representable.

12:54.300 --> 12:58.840
But I feel like it was a pretty nice grid.

12:58.980 --> 13:02.420
I don't think you can really complain about being second.

13:02.420 --> 13:04.980
I mean, everyone wants to be first, but…

13:04.980 --> 13:08.240
Like when you have Freddie Slater on the grid, it's kind of hard to be first.

13:08.240 --> 13:16.760
But we also have quite a few other drivers that did FRECA last season, who were worse than him, and they're still on the F3 grid.

13:16.760 --> 13:28.320
So if we say de Palo was runner-up, and we look at other drivers later who also competed at FRECA, he's kind of expected to maybe not do better than him.

13:28.980 --> 13:30.780
Get a few podiums, maybe.

13:30.780 --> 13:34.880
I'd say, you know, for maybe him, get a few podiums, maybe a win, you know.

13:34.880 --> 13:37.540
Just have a decent, strong season.

13:37.540 --> 13:44.040
And as for Stromsted, he was the second strongest driver last year in Trident, finishing sixth.

13:44.040 --> 13:47.840
Wurz was like... Wurz was 13th, he was way off.

13:47.840 --> 13:56.340
I just remember Wurz was right behind Camara a handful of times, and they told him to keep the position and to not attack.

13:56.340 --> 13:59.400
And that kind of... that kind of bugged me a bit.

13:59.400 --> 14:01.440
What is Wurz even doing this year?

14:01.440 --> 14:07.640
Isn't he doing something Super Formula? I don't know if he does Super Formula or Super Formula Lights.

14:07.640 --> 14:10.660
He's doing Super Formula and Super GT.

14:11.300 --> 14:16.800
But I feel like Stromsted was really forgotten last year.

14:16.800 --> 14:20.700
I feel like he was there, but I mean, I just looked at the grid.

14:20.700 --> 14:24.080
And the thing is, everyone talked about, like, Camara, Tsolov.

14:24.080 --> 14:26.120
I talked about Tramnitz the f***ing time.

14:26.120 --> 14:34.100
And they're still favourites from other teams, but I feel like him being Danish didn't really help him with anyone but my father, who really likes him.

14:34.100 --> 14:35.060
Yeah, but he was solid.

14:35.060 --> 14:42.960
He was really solid, but he was, like, midfield solid, and that's sadly not enough for a lot of people, especially if your teammate is the champion.

14:42.960 --> 14:47.800
He's, like, one of those drivers the same way with Nael, who, you know, had a first season.

14:47.800 --> 14:52.480
It was alright, and, you know, people that are really, really attentive to F3 will be like:

14:52.480 --> 14:55.700
“Hey, he can really do a step up this year.”

14:55.700 --> 14:58.580
I can see him finishing in the top five.

14:58.580 --> 15:05.840
But if you're not a hardcore watcher every single weekend, and you know every single name, you're not really remembering him.

15:05.840 --> 15:09.660
I think for him, it's very much, can he build on from last season?

15:09.660 --> 15:15.500
He needs to improve, because he can't, you know, you're finishing sixth in kind of the best car, and in the end, you know,

15:15.500 --> 15:17.960
Trident were easily the fastest last year.

15:17.960 --> 15:21.580
But they finished second in the team's championship, which…

15:21.740 --> 15:34.300
But as I've also mentioned with Wurz, they were kind of really acting all in favour of Camara, which is, you know, he was, especially Totsdian, who was the title favourite.

15:34.300 --> 15:39.560
They wanted him to get that title as soon as possible and support him.

15:39.560 --> 15:46.860
And, I mean, I don't know how much Mercedes actually, you know, still did with him towards the end of the season.

15:46.860 --> 15:54.300
So it's kind of... And I think the grid last season, with quite a few really good guys, it was really competitive.

15:54.300 --> 15:58.420
And it was difficult, especially after, like, the summer when…

15:58.420 --> 16:05.660
It wasn't after summer, actually, because I always talk about it was after summer, but when Boya finally really showed up, and suddenly he was, like, crazy fast.

16:05.660 --> 16:09.340
And then I'd say this year's grid is even stronger, I feel like.

16:09.340 --> 16:13.460
Yeah, the grid this year is pretty good. So let's see what he can do, I guess.

16:13.600 --> 16:24.360
Yeah, because, like, when you look at MP, I'd say all three, you know, they're quite solid drivers, they're good drivers, and I feel like, I don't know, you're kind of Colanaghi, Taponen, Giusti, any of them.

16:24.360 --> 16:26.020
Yeah, that was a really good segue.

16:26.020 --> 16:31.440
I have a question. Is Taponen still with the Ferrari Driver Academy?

16:31.440 --> 16:32.860
Yes, he is.

16:32.860 --> 16:36.360
Okay, okay, that influences my opinion of him a bit.

16:36.600 --> 16:43.240
What I'm saying is that I really, really like the Ferrari Driver Academy, actually, not necessarily their drivers.

16:43.240 --> 16:51.240
But, I really think the Academy itself is really good, because whenever you see videos of them, it's like, oh, we sent all the drivers on a training camp.

16:51.240 --> 16:58.100
Every single one of our drivers, you know, gets support in, they all get the shoes from Puma sponsored, you know.

16:58.100 --> 17:06.980
They all get, like, crazy training camps, where I'm pretty sure, if you're a driver, it really, really helps you to have this guidance by yourself.

17:06.980 --> 17:11.350
Because it is guidance, because it is really the opportunity that you get from the team.

17:11.350 --> 17:19.320
And I think that if Taponen were to not have that, I would expect him to do worse than he does while he does have that.

17:19.440 --> 17:26.330
And I think this season, especially, I think he's the only Ferrari Driver Academy member in F3, right?

17:26.330 --> 17:29.020
Uh, yeah, he's the only one.

17:29.020 --> 17:38.900
Like, last season, he was kind of also second to Camara, because obviously, the Ferrari Driver Academy also mainly cared about, you know, where’s Camara, they wanted him to win.

17:38.900 --> 17:44.140
But this season, if they can support him, they will, because he's like their main guy in the series.

17:44.140 --> 17:46.560
They'll be like, let's f***ing go with him.

17:46.880 --> 17:52.240
And we know Taponen can be, he did quite well in Formula Regional two years ago, I think it was.

17:52.240 --> 17:55.140
And I think last year, he did struggle a bit.

17:55.140 --> 17:57.280
But then again, now, he's a returning driver.

17:57.280 --> 17:59.880
And second year, you can do wonders sometimes.

17:59.880 --> 18:01.660
So it's like, can you build on that?

18:01.660 --> 18:04.940
I kind of really rate him on the same area as Stromsted.

18:04.940 --> 18:07.820
Because to me, they're just, like, really similar, actually.

18:07.820 --> 18:09.400
Because I don't know where that's from.

18:09.400 --> 18:16.300
But they kind of, you know, they were both with top team academies, but didn't get, like, 100% of the attention of that.

18:16.520 --> 18:18.480
And they're really solid drivers, I think.

18:18.480 --> 18:22.720
But especially last season, they kind of went under the radar of casual fans.

18:22.720 --> 18:26.560
And I really think he looks like that one prince from the British Crown family.

18:26.560 --> 18:29.680
And that's really important to me, because it always freaks me out.

18:29.680 --> 18:31.760
Yeah, I mean, but he is an interesting one.

18:31.760 --> 18:34.610
Even, I mean, Colanaghi, you know, he's a Red Bull junior.

18:34.610 --> 18:35.760
He dominated.

18:35.760 --> 18:42.110
He won Eurocup 3 last year, even though he didn't show up for the last round, because he was at Macau.

18:42.110 --> 18:43.540
So he just wasn't there.

18:43.540 --> 18:44.590
Just didn't show up.

18:44.590 --> 18:46.110
Yeah, he just wasn't there.

18:46.110 --> 18:46.880
He was at Macau.

18:46.880 --> 18:48.780
And he ended up P4 in Macau.

18:48.780 --> 18:52.280
So, like, I'd say he's pretty good.

18:52.800 --> 18:59.820
He does have the disadvantage of being a rookie versus Taponen and Giusti, who are both in their second seasons.

18:59.820 --> 19:04.420
But I do expect to see some, like, good performances from him.

19:04.420 --> 19:10.900
Also, I've just realized that all three of MP's drivers are backed by F1 driver academies.

19:10.900 --> 19:12.740
Oh, I was about to say that as well.

19:12.740 --> 19:18.300
Like, you have Colanaghi with Red Bull, Taponen with Ferrari, and Giusti with Williams.

19:18.300 --> 19:22.220
Can you repeat his name, please, so I know how to pronounce it?

19:22.220 --> 19:23.090
Colangahi..

19:23.090 --> 19:24.040
Colanaghi..

19:24.040 --> 19:32.440
Well, I think that he has the advantage that Eurocup 3, you know, like, FRECA actually does drive.

19:32.440 --> 19:38.180
I think they drive quite a few of the European circuits, so that should actually really help him.

19:38.380 --> 19:41.590
And I know we always talk like rookies don't necessarily do so well.

19:41.590 --> 19:47.900
But I think, I have a feeling that Red Bull is also one of the teams that I think can really support their juniors.

19:47.900 --> 19:49.920
And we've seen quite a few of them do pretty well.

19:49.920 --> 19:51.660
I have a feeling he will do good.

19:51.660 --> 19:54.700
Yeah, they raced at four of the F3 circuits.

19:54.700 --> 19:58.220
Red Bull Ring, Monza, Spa, and Barcelona.

19:58.220 --> 20:03.080
If you're a Red Bull junior, they will shoot you if you don't do well around Red Bull Ring.

20:03.080 --> 20:04.040
That's the point.

20:04.260 --> 20:08.420
And I think also the Red Bull academy, like Ferrari, like you were saying, they do something to do.

20:08.420 --> 20:10.350
I always see on, like, you know, wheels and stuff.

20:10.350 --> 20:12.200
They have their, you know, training camps.

20:12.200 --> 20:19.680
I feel like Red Bull is more on like the side of where they- I mean, they do have really good sports facilities.

20:19.680 --> 20:24.110
Because I always post the videos of, you know, here's the drivers working out.

20:24.110 --> 20:28.540
And, you know, they show them in their, like, little Red Bull branded gym.

20:28.540 --> 20:35.240
And they do a lot of stuff where they let them just do VR stuff, which is maybe good for them monetarily.

20:35.240 --> 20:37.900
But I think they also have a good simulator probably.

20:37.900 --> 20:43.590
Maybe they, like, call up Max and ask him, you know, what's, what's the simulator.

20:44.880 --> 20:46.380
Max Verstappen on speed dial.

20:46.380 --> 20:51.960
Imagine you're in Red Bull and you can probably, like, not directly ask him.

20:51.960 --> 20:55.560
But you do have, like, his data as reference point.

20:55.560 --> 20:59.300
And they're like, you know, look how Max drives that corner.

20:59.300 --> 21:02.110
And he got pole by a second.

21:02.110 --> 21:03.500
Try that too.

21:03.500 --> 21:04.800
And I'm just bullsh*t talking.

21:04.800 --> 21:05.460
We should go on.

21:05.460 --> 21:08.000
So do we want to move on to ART?

21:08.000 --> 21:08.610
Yeah.

21:08.610 --> 21:10.240
ART, you know, one of the.

21:10.240 --> 21:11.610
What happens at ART?

21:11.610 --> 21:13.830
They have three rookies.

21:14.300 --> 21:17.640
Well, there are quite a few teams with an all rookie line-up this year.

21:17.640 --> 21:25.140
I mean, my first point about them is a criticism, I'd say, because I am disappointed there is no Evan Gilitare.

21:25.140 --> 21:29.780
He has some funding issues, so he's competing in Super Formula Lights.

21:29.780 --> 21:35.590
But, I mean, I feel like he is kind of a, he was probably one of the strongest drivers in FRECA last year.

21:35.590 --> 21:39.780
Unfortunately, the team couldn't deliver, but he did win in the Middle East.

21:40.200 --> 21:43.580
With the funding issues, with the funding issues thing.

21:43.580 --> 21:48.260
Same thing with Akshay Bohra, who I think should have been on the F3 grid.

21:48.260 --> 21:51.880
But he also is doing Super Formula Lights instead.

21:52.540 --> 22:00.600
I mean, I saw someone say that, you know, whatever team he's with in Super Formula does like an exchange with ART.

22:00.600 --> 22:07.780
Like, I think it's, is it Kato who's like, from, wait, before I say something stupid, I need to look something up.

22:07.940 --> 22:13.260
Yeah, I mean, we have Gladys, who, he did win the Winter Series in EC3 last year.

22:13.260 --> 22:17.400
But then, in the main season, his performance was not quite replicated.

22:17.400 --> 22:22.700
So, of course, you know, Winter Series and the main season are kind of extremely different.

22:22.700 --> 22:27.880
Because, just before he’s, just because he's performing in the winter, that's a lot more condensed.

22:27.880 --> 22:32.060
People maybe don't care as much about the Winter Series as opposed to the main series.

22:32.320 --> 22:36.680
But, you know, I just looked at it, and it's neither of the F3 drivers.

22:36.680 --> 22:45.040
But I swear, I saw someone talk about how ART takes up drivers from, because they have, like, they have, like, connection with, I don't remember which one.

22:45.040 --> 22:48.220
But with a team from Asia, from, like, Japan.

22:48.220 --> 22:56.640
And that they kind of take up drivers from them and, like, do s*** with them in Europe, where ART has more experience.

22:56.640 --> 23:01.860
And, like, this is the first time that European driver has, you know, been sent over.

23:01.980 --> 23:05.280
Like, they do, like, in little exchange, and it's really nice.

23:05.280 --> 23:12.060
And, like, I saw some people talk about either that'll allow him to, like, have a really nice career over in Japan.

23:12.060 --> 23:16.420
You know, if you do really well in Super Formula, maybe it's not F1.

23:16.420 --> 23:23.320
But, you know, we see quite a few really good guys from those championships do their stuff also in GT over the world.

23:23.320 --> 23:26.440
And also in endurance racing and, like, hyper cars.

23:26.440 --> 23:30.860
So, I think, you know, it's maybe not F1, but I think it's still a really good way for him.

23:31.020 --> 23:34.800
And I'm really disappointed at how sh**ty the funding situation is.

23:34.800 --> 23:38.460
Yeah, I feel like with this ART lineup, I mean, it's not like that.

23:38.460 --> 23:45.400
Like, I'd say they're decent because, I mean, all three of them finished top 10 in their main series last year.

23:45.600 --> 23:49.560
I mean, I think Kato and Le were, like, ninth and seventh respectively.

23:49.560 --> 23:52.440
So, it's like, they're not awful by any means.

23:52.440 --> 23:54.860
But it's like, that is kind of there.

23:54.860 --> 24:05.180
I think they'll be midfield drivers because they're on the advantage that I think none of them has any priority in the team.

24:05.180 --> 24:06.660
Where it's like…

24:06.660 --> 24:07.800
No academy support.

24:07.800 --> 24:09.560
Yeah, not just that.

24:09.560 --> 24:17.400
Like, if you look at it, you know, like, last season, like, Laurens van Hoepen was, you know, in his second season.

24:17.400 --> 24:22.760
So, the team kind of maybe didn't support him, but he had that advantage of experience.

24:22.760 --> 24:30.380
So, he was automatically kind of doing something where his teammates maybe weren't quite able to do the same.

24:30.380 --> 24:33.720
But they're all rookies, you know, they're all known.

24:33.720 --> 24:35.820
They all are in favourites for the title.

24:35.820 --> 24:40.540
Yeah, and they all finished around the same position in their respective championships as well.

24:40.540 --> 24:42.700
Kind of, like, lower half of the top 10.

24:42.700 --> 24:45.760
Yeah, I mean, I feel like we'll just see them somewhere.

24:45.760 --> 24:48.080
Yeah, but they'll be there.

24:48.080 --> 24:52.760
And also, even if we wanted them to do well, I don't trust ART.

24:52.760 --> 24:55.900
Yeah, ART is very much a midfield team as well.

24:55.900 --> 24:58.840
So, they're just going to be there, I feel like.

24:58.840 --> 25:00.080
They're just there with the vibes.

25:00.080 --> 25:01.840
Maybe a random podium.

25:01.840 --> 25:04.640
So, we talked a bit about Akshay Bohra.

25:04.640 --> 25:09.480
Let's switch over to his ex-teammate from last year, Enzo Deligny.

25:09.480 --> 25:11.740
That was not such a smooth switch.

25:11.740 --> 25:13.080
Tried, okay.

25:13.080 --> 25:14.540
I tried, I tried.

25:14.540 --> 25:15.100
I tried.

25:15.920 --> 25:18.320
But yeah, let's go to VAR.

25:18.320 --> 25:22.020
Everyone gets allowed one crashout in this one.

25:22.020 --> 25:23.860
And it's your…

25:23.860 --> 25:25.700
What's the English term for it?

25:25.700 --> 25:27.240
Your floor?

25:27.240 --> 25:29.300
The floor is yours.

25:29.300 --> 25:30.240
It's my turn.

25:30.240 --> 25:31.300
The floor is yours, great.

25:31.300 --> 25:32.400
Okay.

25:32.400 --> 25:39.780
So, obviously, the big storyline of VAR is Deligny’s whole PREMA thing.

25:39.780 --> 25:52.120
And for anyone listening who is not super active on Twitter, the whole “PREMA is good bro calm” tweet originally came from a reply to me.

25:52.340 --> 25:54.700
Because I was upset that he was joining PREMA.

25:54.700 --> 25:58.820
Because, as we all know, PREMA has not been very good recently.

25:58.820 --> 26:01.320
So, I was upset that he was joining PREMA.

26:01.320 --> 26:07.480
And the guy himself replied to me being like, PREMA is good bro calm.

26:07.860 --> 26:12.820
And so, fast forward a couple months, PREMA is not good.

26:12.820 --> 26:14.760
No one is calm.

26:14.760 --> 26:17.640
And he's left the team.

26:17.640 --> 26:19.720
But yeah.

26:19.720 --> 26:24.520
So, he moved to VAR after so many rumors.

26:24.520 --> 26:26.360
And no one really knew what was happening.

26:26.360 --> 26:27.400
But yeah.

26:27.400 --> 26:30.560
I'm going to get a tattoo of that tweet.

26:30.560 --> 26:33.080
PREMA was obviously not good bro.

26:33.080 --> 26:34.500
And he jumped ship.

26:34.500 --> 26:36.260
A feeder series hall of fame, really.

26:36.260 --> 26:37.800
Top ten moments.

26:37.800 --> 26:38.740
Exactly.

26:38.740 --> 26:41.380
But yeah.

26:41.380 --> 26:47.180
Just the beauties of social media that you can interact with drivers like this.

26:47.180 --> 26:51.260
And then you're reminded that they're just unserious teenagers.

26:51.260 --> 26:52.580
Yeah, exactly.

26:52.580 --> 27:00.260
Because, like, if you're just on Twitter, like, some of Enzo's replies, like, he's just using memes by the situation.

27:00.660 --> 27:03.200
He really is just, like, peak 17-year-old boy.

27:03.200 --> 27:04.460
I know, he is.

27:04.460 --> 27:08.720
And I think that also reminds us a lot of this humanity of this driver's cause.

27:08.720 --> 27:10.800
You know, like, at least in F1, you know, they're more polished.

27:10.800 --> 27:11.700
They're adults.

27:11.700 --> 27:12.700
They're more professional.

27:12.700 --> 27:15.240
F3, that's 16 and 17.

27:15.240 --> 27:16.140
These guys are teenagers.

27:16.140 --> 27:17.560
Yeah, that's what he's saying.

27:17.560 --> 27:19.540
They're 16, 17-year-olds.

27:19.540 --> 27:23.160
He's probably saying, you know, he's saying “bludski”.

27:25.660 --> 27:33.000
The whole, like, FIA test thingy that they were doing and didn't know, like, the answers to that.

27:33.000 --> 27:34.640
What was going on with that?

27:34.640 --> 27:35.900
Give me a test of that.

27:35.900 --> 27:37.340
I would have passed it.

27:37.340 --> 27:39.260
I would have freestyled it.

27:39.260 --> 27:43.020
I saw, like, the questions.

27:43.020 --> 27:48.260
Like, I saw two questions on Twitter and they were in French, but I translated them and they didn't seem that bad.

27:48.260 --> 27:49.800
So I don't know what's going on with that.

27:49.800 --> 27:52.080
They're all stupid and didn't go to school.

27:52.080 --> 27:56.760
I mean, if it's anything like driving theory, it's common sense, I feel.

27:56.760 --> 27:58.300
But you have to imagine that.

27:58.300 --> 28:00.480
I have a few questions about this.

28:00.860 --> 28:08.740
First question, are all the questions in English or is there any option to have them, like, in your language?

28:08.740 --> 28:15.660
Because I could imagine that, especially if you speak a language that's, like, far removed from English or you don't speak English well,

28:15.660 --> 28:23.740
if the questions are not in, like, a language you speak well, it can be very difficult, especially if it's on technical terms.

28:23.740 --> 28:30.000
Second question, have we considered that majority of them has not really been in school?

28:30.680 --> 28:34.720
But, like, the thing is, the questions that I saw, it was like, um, what was it?

28:34.720 --> 28:41.400
Like, one of the questions I saw was, if you won a race but then got penalized but then still ended up on the podium, what do you do?

28:41.400 --> 28:45.380
Do you, like, cuss out the stewards or do you just celebrate your podium?

28:45.380 --> 28:48.020
No, I'm going to go punch the stewards.

28:48.020 --> 28:50.940
Yeah, I'm going to go crash into someone.

28:50.940 --> 28:53.520
I'm going to go show them my fist.

28:53.520 --> 28:59.400
You have to consider, you have to consider quite a few of these drivers, with all due respect,

29:00.500 --> 29:06.000
do not go into school and care a lot about English and English text understanding.

29:06.000 --> 29:13.740
Like, they read that and, you know, you can mix words up and you can completely misunderstand such a question.

29:13.740 --> 29:15.920
But the whole thing, it's so funny.

29:15.920 --> 29:20.320
It's so, like, in a school or university group chat call, who's got the answers?

29:20.320 --> 29:22.760
Yeah guys, does everyone have the answers?

29:22.760 --> 29:24.060
Does everyone know what's going on?

29:24.600 --> 29:28.820
When I'm in university, I always let the other students do my online tests.

29:28.820 --> 29:33.420
Not because I'm lazy, but because they study more serious sh*t than me.

29:33.420 --> 29:35.160
That actually happened once.

29:35.160 --> 29:39.960
Yeah, and I feel like within VAR, Deligny, am I saying his name right?

29:39.960 --> 29:40.900
Wait, wait, wait.

29:40.900 --> 29:42.220
How do you say his name?

29:42.220 --> 29:43.740
Because I've seen everything.

29:43.980 --> 29:54.220
I thought it was de-line-e, but I saw what I heard one commentator call him de-lick-nee, which is what I call him when I want to make fun of him.

29:54.220 --> 29:58.140
But, like, Robin says, what did you say?

29:58.140 --> 30:00.100
Because it was not de-line-e.

30:00.480 --> 30:07.860
I've been saying de-lean-e, because that's what I heard, like, when I was first watching FRECA, and also during Macau, that's what they were calling him.

30:07.860 --> 30:10.720
Maybe we should ask him to send us a voice note.

30:10.720 --> 30:12.340
Who called him de-lick-nee?

30:12.340 --> 30:17.620
The FRECA commentator switched to de-lick-nee at the end of the season, and it was so weird.

30:17.620 --> 30:19.340
Who is he licking?

30:19.340 --> 30:21.600
Who’s knees are he licking?

30:21.600 --> 30:29.260
So, about the, about, I'm going to call him de-line-e, and if he has a problem with that, I have Twitter, I don't give a f***.

30:30.480 --> 30:31.040
Yeah, exactly.

30:31.040 --> 30:35.160
He'll just, like, tag you on Twitter, being like, that's not how you say my name.

30:35.160 --> 30:41.440
Can we get him on, just for him to explain how, you know, how we can say his name, please?

30:41.440 --> 30:47.800
I think he would very much be the lead driver within that team, because he did really well in the

30:47.800 --> 30:49.980
He was third in FRECA last year.

30:49.980 --> 30:56.020
He is a good driver, and, I mean, he's abandoned PREMA, which was very much the smart idea to do.

30:56.020 --> 30:59.180
I mean, del Pino is, again, he's just sort of there.

30:59.980 --> 31:12.440
I want to point out about Van Amfersfoort in general that, if I look back at last season, like, they were not necessarily, like, the best.

31:12.440 --> 31:25.540
I need to check something, how they actually performed, so I can really judge it, but I don't have them in mind as, I mean, they also did not have, like, the best drivers yet.

31:25.540 --> 31:30.180
Nael, Santiago Ramos, and Ivan Dominguez.

31:30.640 --> 31:34.880
And I feel like Nael was kind of a right place in the championship.

31:34.880 --> 31:36.760
He was top eight.

31:36.760 --> 31:40.400
I think Deligny can maybe do something like that.

31:40.400 --> 31:42.100
I mean, Del Pino was, like…

31:42.100 --> 31:44.100
Yeah, I also expect it.

31:44.800 --> 31:51.520
But I, sadly, don't think that, just because of the machinery, that he will be able to fight for the championship.

31:51.520 --> 31:54.260
Even, I mean, he has a bit of a disadvantage.

31:54.260 --> 31:56.320
He's, you know, he's a rookie.

31:56.320 --> 31:59.580
He, you know, it's difficult.

31:59.580 --> 32:01.360
He doesn't have all that sponsoring, you know.

32:02.740 --> 32:13.360
He does not have a teammate that he could really learn quite a lot of, where he could say, hey, I'm doing, like, this season as, like, just a throwaway season just to learn the circuits and stuff.

32:13.360 --> 32:23.180
But I think that he should be able to be, like, top ten and, like, you know, do a solid P9 championship and hopefully join a stronger team next season.

32:23.180 --> 32:26.480
Similar to what Niall has done, that's what he can aim for.

32:26.480 --> 32:30.900
Because, I mean, Del Pino is, like, very much lower midfield last year.

32:30.900 --> 32:32.640
Lower midfield, I mean…

32:32.640 --> 32:35.380
I think, wasn't Del Pino the lowest MP?

32:35.380 --> 32:37.640
I think so, I mean…

32:37.640 --> 32:40.980
He finished 20-something last year.

32:40.980 --> 32:48.280
Yeah, he was the lowest MP by far, because Tramnitz was fourth.

32:48.280 --> 32:49.640
Should have been third.

32:49.640 --> 32:53.880
Giusti was 10th, and Del Pino was 23rd.

32:53.880 --> 33:00.400
I know that at some point, something happened where he was, like, where people were, like, “oh, he shouldn't have gotten a penalty or something.”

33:00.600 --> 33:03.840
And I think at some point his lap time was deleted or something.

33:03.840 --> 33:06.840
So he started from the back for two races.

33:06.840 --> 33:11.280
But he barely, very rarely got points.

33:11.280 --> 33:12.780
He only got one podium.

33:12.780 --> 33:20.500
And his best finish was eighth in the Spa sprint race.

33:21.500 --> 33:24.600
He did have a P2, Imola sprint.

33:24.600 --> 33:26.000
Oh, yeah.

33:26.000 --> 33:26.700
I'm sorry.

33:26.700 --> 33:30.200
Yeah, I was looking at, like, when he was points finish.

33:30.200 --> 33:31.600
When he did points finish.

33:31.600 --> 33:33.160
Why the f**k did he get it?

33:33.160 --> 33:36.240
Yeah, I mean, Camara did nothing in that race.

33:36.660 --> 33:37.620
Boya retired.

33:37.620 --> 33:42.460
And quite a few of the other typical front runners had a really bad race.

33:42.460 --> 33:43.540
It was Imola.

33:43.540 --> 33:47.300
Imola's always crazy, but that was his best.

33:47.300 --> 33:56.960
And other than that, he only did get points in three other races, which were, yeah, it was not that good, I think.

33:56.960 --> 34:11.260
I mean, especially if you compare it, because I know MP was not the best in general, but let's compare him just out of fairness to Giusti, because I think it's unfair to put him on a level with Tramnitz.

34:11.960 --> 34:14.980
But, I mean, Giusti pretty regularly got points.

34:14.980 --> 34:16.690
He got two podiums.

34:16.690 --> 34:26.670
He was, like, often in, like, you know, somewhere between P6 and P10, which is a solid place to be in, what I expect from an MP driver.

34:26.670 --> 34:35.120
But I feel like Van Amersfoort is even worse than MP, so that's, it's not looking good for him.

34:35.360 --> 34:43.940
I think he will be in a pretty similar position in a championship, again, similar, mainly just because he has that experience.

34:43.940 --> 34:53.000
But I'm going to look for the other two drivers, because I swear they were also down in the 20s, Ramos and Domingues.

34:53.000 --> 34:56.260
Domingues was 19th, and Ramos was 15th.

34:56.260 --> 34:58.360
And Ramos had two wins.

34:58.360 --> 35:03.600
Yeah, I mean, it's very much like your midfield team, you know, you take maybe.

35:04.320 --> 35:09.320
I think the aim for, like, let's be getting a few solid points from this year, just be consistent.

35:09.320 --> 35:13.440
And then he can move up a team for next year very much.

35:13.440 --> 35:25.600
I mean, it would be his third season, so if he does not, you know, prove anything this season, I think F2 looks very unlikely for him.

35:25.600 --> 35:27.020
You never know.

35:28.400 --> 35:34.060
I mean, maybe he magically makes up a step and gets in a top ten.

35:34.060 --> 35:36.690
Look at the F2 reserve, anything can happen.

35:36.690 --> 35:37.380
You know what?

35:37.380 --> 35:37.940
Exactly.

35:37.940 --> 35:40.000
He can go to F2, I don't give a f**k.

35:40.000 --> 35:41.840
Let's go on.

35:41.840 --> 35:43.020
Rodin.

35:43.020 --> 35:47.840
I mean, Badoer, I mean, he's been doing surprisingly well in test-.

35:47.840 --> 35:49.600
I mean, of course, testing is testing.

35:49.600 --> 35:52.520
It doesn't mean too much, but…

35:52.520 --> 35:55.640
I have one-sided beef with him.

35:55.640 --> 35:56.540
Why?

35:56.540 --> 35:59.020
Spa, do you not remember Spa?

35:59.020 --> 36:00.230
He was at…

36:00.230 --> 36:00.900
Oh, yeah, of course.

36:00.900 --> 36:04.960
One of the worst moments of my life.

36:04.960 --> 36:07.520
Yeah, Badoer is…

36:08.060 --> 36:10.380
I mean, last year, he was…

36:10.380 --> 36:13.190
Do you need to go further on that?

36:13.190 --> 36:18.920
Because I feel like if you listen to this, it's just going to sound again like I'm absolutely insane.

36:18.920 --> 36:22.710
I mean, Clerot I feel like, he's the rookie in the team.

36:22.710 --> 36:24.420
He had a solid…

36:24.420 --> 36:26.860
I mean, he was fourth in FREC last year.

36:26.860 --> 36:28.980
FRECA, whatever you want to call it.

36:28.980 --> 36:30.730
Last season was still FRECA.

36:30.730 --> 36:32.230
FRECA, yeah there

36:32.230 --> 36:36.710
I've written FRECA down for some reason, so it's like, oh, it's FREC now.

36:36.710 --> 36:44.320
But no, last year was FRECA , so all of the FRECA front winners are now coming up to F3, apart from Giltaire.

36:44.320 --> 36:46.300
I think Rodin is pretty…

36:46.300 --> 36:48.620
I think they won’t do quite a lot.

36:48.620 --> 36:52.840
I mean, Christian Ho is the same guy who was at DAMS last season, no?

36:52.840 --> 36:53.960
Yeah.

36:53.960 --> 36:56.340
Yeah, I mean, it was DAMS.

36:56.340 --> 36:57.640
What are we supposed to say?

36:57.640 --> 37:03.920
I don't know, but we can move on to the juicy one in PREMA, where Enzo ran away from.

37:04.560 --> 37:07.320
Cause PREMA, there's stuff to say about, I feel like.

37:07.320 --> 37:09.300
Okay, I'm deeply upset.

37:09.300 --> 37:12.000
That's how we are starting this.

37:12.000 --> 37:12.840
All right?

37:12.840 --> 37:13.980
Deeply upset.

37:13.980 --> 37:16.260
First of all, you know what?

37:16.260 --> 37:18.380
We had a pretty good lineup at first, you know?

37:18.380 --> 37:22.260
I'm not the biggest fan of, personally, Wharton.

37:22.260 --> 37:26.460
But Wharton, Sharp, you know, that was okay.

37:26.620 --> 37:28.780
Deligny, that would have been a great lineup.

37:28.780 --> 37:29.300
De-lick-knee?

37:29.300 --> 37:30.580
De-lick-knee.

37:30.580 --> 37:33.540
Why is he licking knees?

37:33.540 --> 37:35.000
Shut up.

37:35.000 --> 37:35.840
Shut up.

37:35.840 --> 37:50.960
But I swear to God, him leaving to VAR single-handedly dropped PREMA from what could have been a top five, maybe, team finish, to, like, way down the bottom at, like, seven.

37:51.440 --> 37:51.730
Okay?

37:51.730 --> 37:53.960
Because there is no way.

37:53.960 --> 37:55.540
I've never heard of this guy.

37:55.540 --> 37:55.920
Okay?

37:55.920 --> 37:56.540
Sorry.

37:56.540 --> 38:03.300
For those who are unaware, the lineup next year for PREMA is Sharp, Wharton, and who's that guy?

38:03.300 --> 38:04.080
Garfias?

38:04.560 --> 38:07.940
Yeah, he did Euro Formula Open last year.

38:07.940 --> 38:09.520
Euro Formula Open?

38:09.520 --> 38:12.060
That is not a real championship.

38:12.060 --> 38:15.960
And I think PREMA, overall, are a team who…

38:15.960 --> 38:16.660
Are dying!

38:16.660 --> 38:17.460
Are dying!

38:17.460 --> 38:20.380
Yeah, I mean, we see in IndyCar they’re-

38:20.380 --> 38:22.340
They ain't there in St. Pete.

38:22.340 --> 38:24.060
They're not there in St. Pete.

38:24.400 --> 38:31.440
They're not on the entry list for any, like, of the upcoming, like, races, as far as I can tell.

38:31.440 --> 38:37.320
As much as I would like to be like, oh, you know, “Callum Illott’s being weird about it. That means he's probably going to be racing.”

38:37.320 --> 38:39.190
That doesn't mean anything.

38:39.190 --> 38:45.690
So, financially speaking, and as just a general thing, they are failing…

38:45.690 --> 38:46.260
Not failing.

38:46.260 --> 38:48.260
They are degrading.

38:48.260 --> 38:51.400
As a team, they're not doing very well.

38:51.920 --> 38:55.670
I'd say they're wilting, because, I mean, their karting team is now gone.

38:55.670 --> 39:04.920
And you see, across their lineups, I mean, apart from in FREC, their lineups are quite weak compared to the traditional PREMA, I would say.

39:04.920 --> 39:09.980
I'd say Formula 1 Academy is also pretty alright at the moment.

39:09.980 --> 39:15.420
Yeah, I think it's, in F1 Academy, because they always announce, oh, you're Mercedes or you're PUMA.

39:15.420 --> 39:17.520
I have no clue who's with what team.

39:17.520 --> 39:21.300
Actually, we're still missing one, I think.

39:21.300 --> 39:24.440
Yeah, because we have Paatz and Westcott.

39:24.440 --> 39:30.170
Matilda Paatz is pretty nice, and Peyton Westcott also seems pretty good.

39:30.170 --> 39:32.730
So, I think it should be good.

39:32.730 --> 39:34.600
Yeah, my bad, yeah.

39:34.600 --> 39:42.080
As I said, F1 Academy, I don't know who's driving for what team, because the brand is like, oh, you're the Lego team.

39:42.420 --> 39:44.080
Anyway, let's go back to PREMA.

39:44.080 --> 39:51.900
I just opened my list of all the drivers who drove for PREMA in the past, and, you know, where they are now.

39:51.900 --> 39:54.860
And it's like, they could fill their own F1 grid.

39:55.210 --> 39:57.440
Look at PREMA in 2024.

39:57.440 --> 40:04.340
In 2024, you had Antonelli and Bearman in F2, and F3, you had Mini, Lindblad, and Beganovic.

40:04.500 --> 40:07.980
Three of those five drivers are on the F1 grid this year.

40:07.980 --> 40:15.190
And the other two are also good, because even if it's not F1 for them, I mean, I really expect Mini to go to FE or something.

40:15.190 --> 40:17.280
I think we mentioned it last round, so…

40:17.280 --> 40:18.020
FE, yeah.

40:18.020 --> 40:19.020
Nissan FE.

40:19.020 --> 40:20.760
But they're good drivers.

40:21.020 --> 40:22.320
I rate them for something.

40:22.320 --> 40:23.480
Who is Garfias?

40:23.480 --> 40:25.260
Where is he going?

40:25.260 --> 40:27.780
Who is Garfias, bro?

40:27.780 --> 40:29.100
I've never heard of this guy.

40:29.100 --> 40:31.040
He's Abhkazava’ed into my life.

40:31.040 --> 40:38.340
Like, the weakest driver of PREMA 2024 is probably stronger than their best driver this year in F2, F3.

40:38.340 --> 40:42.500
Yeah, and I mean, if you look at F3 2024, they all had team backing.

40:42.500 --> 40:44.080
They had, like, huge teams.

40:44.080 --> 40:45.480
You had a Ferrari driver.

40:45.480 --> 40:46.640
You had a Red Bull driver.

40:46.640 --> 40:48.820
You had a Mercedes driver.

40:48.820 --> 40:49.900
You had an Alpine driver.

40:49.900 --> 40:50.800
You had everything.

40:51.540 --> 40:52.640
Who are these people?

40:52.640 --> 40:53.690
They're just there.

40:53.690 --> 41:03.120
No one of them has any backing of an F1 team, bar their F1 Academy drivers, which is technically another toast, so whatever.

41:03.120 --> 41:13.460
But neither Sharp, nor Wharton, nor Garfias is on that level where they're recognised by huge teams like Red Bull, Ferrari, Alpine,

41:13.460 --> 41:15.280
where they would be like, hey, we want you.

41:15.280 --> 41:20.860
These people even had, you know, back in the day, Mini even had relations to FE teams.

41:20.980 --> 41:22.760
You know, they’re all dead sh*t.

41:22.760 --> 41:24.160
I can't see the same thing.

41:24.160 --> 41:31.760
Out of the bunch, I do think that Sharp should be the highest because Rodin was kind of…

41:31.760 --> 41:33.420
It's shown in testing, too.

41:33.730 --> 41:44.480
And I think Sharp is the kind of driver who could, you know, kind of go somewhere and in another time, he could have had a team backing him.

41:44.480 --> 41:45.420
I mean, things could be different.

41:45.420 --> 41:49.360
But I think, especially for Wharton and Garfias…

41:49.360 --> 41:53.980
And also Sharp, he is a GB3 champion.

41:53.980 --> 41:56.140
So, you know, there is…

41:56.140 --> 41:56.730
There is…

41:56.730 --> 41:58.940
And he's won, you know, British F4.

41:58.940 --> 42:03.060
He did struggle a bit last year, but there is definitely something there.

42:03.140 --> 42:09.500
And I mean, I feel like last year he did underperform to expectations, but there's no reason why he can't improve.

42:09.500 --> 42:12.620
Especially, I mean, given his competition in his team is what?

42:12.620 --> 42:14.360
Garfias and Wharton.

42:14.920 --> 42:17.540
I think he will be by far the best of the bunch.

42:17.540 --> 42:18.980
But I also think…

42:18.980 --> 42:20.580
Let me check something.

42:20.580 --> 42:32.520
I think what my theory was last season, why he was underperforming, was the fact that before that, he pretty much only had experience on British circuits.

42:32.520 --> 42:33.780
Because…

42:33.780 --> 42:34.060
Exactly.

42:34.060 --> 42:38.560
I mean, British F4 obviously only drives in Britain.

42:38.560 --> 42:42.640
And these days they drive in Zandvoort.

42:42.760 --> 42:48.600
But I just looked back and when he drove there, they did not drive in Zandvoort either.

42:48.600 --> 42:49.580
But…

42:49.580 --> 42:53.920
So the only circuit that he knows from British F4 is Silverstone.

42:53.920 --> 43:02.730
In GB3, okay, they did Spa, Hungaroring, and Zandvoort, and Silverstone.

43:02.730 --> 43:11.690
But he's still missing quite a few circuits like Melbourne, Bahrain, Imola, Monza.

43:12.760 --> 43:18.040
Barcelona-Catalunya, Red Bull Ring, Monza.

43:18.040 --> 43:30.160
And the thing is, what I'm also proposing and what I want to talk about when we get to Hitech in a second, and McLaughlin especially, is that circuits are different from each other.

43:30.160 --> 43:35.160
Not just from the way that they're laid out, but also from the way that the car behaves from them.

43:35.160 --> 43:37.940
From the way the tarmac feels if you're in there.

43:38.320 --> 43:40.600
From the way that you handle the tires.

43:40.600 --> 43:50.000
Because how you drive in Bahrain, it's incredibly different from how you drive around Oulton Park.

43:50.000 --> 43:55.540
It's not just in a way that, you know, there's different corners, there's different, you know, straights.

43:55.780 --> 44:01.800
And I think Oulton Park is like kind of, has like a bit of hill, like a bit of change in height.

44:01.800 --> 44:06.820
But the thing is, they also have different times.

44:06.820 --> 44:10.940
I mean, especially Bahrain, it's totally different just from the heat.

44:10.940 --> 44:14.640
That's not something that you experience racing in Britain.

44:15.200 --> 44:21.360
The way that the tires react to that heat is not something that you find when you drive in Britain.

44:21.360 --> 44:27.340
It's, I think, it's something that I imagine as someone who has never driven a Formula car before.

44:27.340 --> 44:39.400
But I have driven streetcars before, and I can tell you that there's a huge difference between, you know, what kind of road you're driving on and what kind of environment you're driving in.

44:39.400 --> 44:43.240
And I imagine it's a huge difference.


44:43.240 --> 44:48.720
Yeah, and I think that Sharp's struggles will be, last year will be something that McLaughlin will experience this year.

44:48.720 --> 44:53.540
Because he is doing quite a, he's doing an even bigger step than what Sharp did.

44:53.540 --> 44:58.380
Because this is going to be McLaughlin's only second ever season in cars.

44:58.380 --> 45:00.280
Because he did British F4 last year.

45:00.280 --> 45:01.760
Of course, he was a champion.

45:01.760 --> 45:04.840
But the year before, he was in karting.

45:04.840 --> 45:12.780
I want to throw back what I said, what I said earlier, before we started to talk.

45:12.980 --> 45:24.600
And that is that, before McLaughlin, Ollie Bearman also did this jump where he, you know, jumped from F4 to F3.

45:25.380 --> 45:27.440
But, yeah, we are at Hitech right now.

45:27.440 --> 45:33.720
But the thing is, before he jumped to F3, Ollie Bearman did, like, two seasons.

45:33.720 --> 45:43.240
He did in, I think it was 2021 where he did ADAC F4, which is like German F4, and British F4 in like his rookie season.

45:43.420 --> 45:48.980
And then 2022, he did full seasons in ADAC F4, and Italian F4.

45:48.980 --> 45:55.940
And I know he won Italian F4, and I know he was really well in German F4.

45:55.940 --> 45:56.980
He won both.

45:56.980 --> 45:58.220
But I'm not sure if he won both.

45:58.220 --> 45:59.020
He did.

45:59.280 --> 46:00.800
I just know that he was on F3.

46:00.800 --> 46:05.400
Okay, the point is, he was also in a really, really strong grid.

46:05.400 --> 46:10.080
And just generally, really, you know, he had experience before coming there.

46:10.080 --> 46:11.380
McLaughlin.

46:11.920 --> 46:14.020
Man, I really like the guy.

46:14.020 --> 46:15.420
I think he's a really good driver.

46:15.420 --> 46:23.540
But I also saw quite a few people saying that they think he's a good driver, but they don't expect a lot of him from F3.

46:23.540 --> 46:25.880
Because it's a huge jump.

46:25.880 --> 46:26.760
And I've said it before.

46:26.760 --> 46:28.940
I've said it when we talked about Colanaghi.

46:28.940 --> 46:32.940
I think he has this huge advantage where he's in Red Bull.

46:32.940 --> 46:36.680
I think he has, you know, he can work with the team.

46:37.300 --> 46:45.960
But I agree, in which I say, I don't think that he will be able to, like, magically fight for the championship.

46:45.960 --> 46:51.200
Especially because Hitech is also not one of the best teams, you know?

46:51.200 --> 46:54.880
I need to check for a minute where Hitech was last year.

46:54.880 --> 46:57.080
They were ninth.

46:57.080 --> 46:58.020
No, eighth.

46:58.020 --> 46:58.960
Oh.

46:58.960 --> 47:04.480
I think the best one was Stenshorne, who did pretty well.

47:04.480 --> 47:05.240
He was, like, fifth.

47:05.660 --> 47:09.480
But the thing is, he also had huge experience before that.

47:09.480 --> 47:12.760
You know, I think the team is a midfield team.

47:12.760 --> 47:17.500
And his biggest struggle is just the lack of experience on the circuit.

47:17.500 --> 47:22.280
And an F4 car to an F3 car is quite a big step up.

47:22.280 --> 47:29.420
I mean, he did do Formula Regional Oceania in New Zealand where he did struggle quite a bit, I'd say.

47:29.420 --> 47:31.220
It was quite evident as well.

47:31.600 --> 47:39.880
For Formula Regional Oceania, it's the same where I say I imagine circuits in Oceania to be really, really different from circuits in Britain.

47:40.520 --> 47:48.620
And I think getting into the car and being on speed is one thing, which is why I want to see him in Silverstone.

47:48.620 --> 47:51.600
And I think I want him to do really well.

47:51.600 --> 47:57.480
But I won't really say anything about his performance unless we're at Silverstone.

47:57.720 --> 48:03.460
Because I expect him to be quite quick around Silverstone, which he should know pretty well.

48:03.460 --> 48:06.320
But everywhere else, I can't really say anything.

48:06.540 --> 48:12.120
I mean, it's very much kind of easier for him to get the experience than probably doing a second F3 season next year.

48:12.120 --> 48:15.400
It's just like, we have to be realistic about him.

48:15.400 --> 48:16.940
Because, you know, he is good.

48:16.940 --> 48:17.440
It's just…

48:17.440 --> 48:20.700
But I think it's maybe not a sh**ty idea to do this.

48:20.700 --> 48:29.720
And, you know, decide on doing two seasons in F3 rather than wasting one season in FREC with the new cars where you don't even know if it's going to be representative.

48:30.660 --> 48:34.520
And it's, you know, directly making the jump, similar to what Tsolov did, actually.

48:34.520 --> 48:37.960
And really getting onto speed in F3.

48:37.960 --> 48:38.820
And then…

48:38.820 --> 48:42.160
I think it'd be a bit close between Nakamura and McLaughlin.

48:42.160 --> 48:45.280
Because Nakamura, of course, has the experience in FRECA. 

48:45.280 --> 48:46.720
Yeah, I can imagine that.

48:46.720 --> 48:51.300
You know, Red Bull does not support him for no reason.

48:51.300 --> 48:53.460
I think he's a pretty good driver.

48:53.460 --> 48:54.540
I think he's…

48:54.540 --> 48:55.280
I really like him.

48:55.280 --> 48:55.760
I rate him.

48:55.760 --> 48:57.820
And I think he's going to do well in the future.

48:58.440 --> 49:03.240
But if he's going to do well in F3 this season, we're going to see.

49:03.240 --> 49:07.140
Let's go to AIX and whatever the hell that line-up is.

49:07.140 --> 49:11.240
I mean, Yevan David, he seems like, you know, he seems like a fun guy.

49:11.240 --> 49:12.640
I like his vibe.

49:12.640 --> 49:13.380
Yeah.

49:13.380 --> 49:16.060
Laughter won't get you to win anything.

49:16.060 --> 49:20.980
Isn't Barrichello Jr. coming from, like, also Formula…

49:20.980 --> 49:22.180
Euro Formula Open?

49:22.180 --> 49:23.220
EFO.

49:23.220 --> 49:27.320
How did he come from Euro Formula Open and only come seventh?

49:27.960 --> 49:31.100
Yeah, and Yevan David was also in Euro Formula Open.

49:31.100 --> 49:32.740
He finished third.

49:32.740 --> 49:33.340
No, second.

49:33.340 --> 49:35.400
Where are all these people coming from?

49:35.400 --> 49:37.640
What happens at Euro Formula Open?

49:37.640 --> 49:37.960
Yeah.

49:37.960 --> 49:38.940
Who won this, actually?

49:38.940 --> 49:40.080
Who won EFO?

49:40.080 --> 49:46.200
I cannot pronounce the name, but it's the cool Polish guy that's doing INDYNXT.

49:46.200 --> 49:48.160
Oh, the one who's afraid of butter?

49:48.160 --> 49:48.700
Him.

49:48.700 --> 49:50.380
Oh, I love him.

49:50.380 --> 49:52.080
I think he's a nice guy.

49:52.880 --> 49:55.260
And even David, he came second.

49:55.260 --> 49:56.540
And…

49:56.540 --> 49:59.200
Yeah, the one who's afraid of butter.

49:59.200 --> 50:00.360
Tymek


50:00.940 --> 50:03.120
Should we just call him that?

50:03.120 --> 50:05.380
I'm just going to call him the butter guy.

50:05.380 --> 50:08.200
You know what's the worst part of this?

50:08.200 --> 50:08.560
What?

50:08.820 --> 50:13.500
Fernando Barrichello is the second worst guy who did a full season.

50:13.500 --> 50:15.320
I mean, he didn't do a full full season.

50:15.320 --> 50:16.580
He missed one race.

50:16.580 --> 50:19.940
But I feel like I wouldn't have changed anything.

50:19.940 --> 50:24.140
Because everyone below him just did like two or three races.

50:24.140 --> 50:26.820
Or like majority less than he did.

50:27.200 --> 50:31.160
It's quite obvious in AIX, I think Benavides is going to be the team leader.

50:31.160 --> 50:32.740
But that's not saying a lot.

50:32.740 --> 50:34.940
Benavides is your team leader.

50:34.940 --> 50:41.240
I mean, he has the experience and he did take two pole positions last year.

50:41.240 --> 50:43.320
I kind of rate.

50:43.320 --> 50:48.980
I don't really rate Benavides, but I think he could be good if he actually did something.

50:48.980 --> 50:52.120
And, you know, oh my God, he was also in Euro Formula Open.

50:52.120 --> 50:53.120
But at least he won.

50:53.120 --> 50:54.000
At least he won.

50:54.000 --> 50:54.400
No.

50:54.580 --> 50:58.180
He was in Euro Formula Open in 2024, but he won.

50:58.180 --> 50:58.580
He won.

50:58.580 --> 50:58.940
Okay.

50:58.940 --> 51:01.980
I mean, at least he brings the experience.

51:01.980 --> 51:03.740
Okay, there were only like five.

51:03.740 --> 51:05.980
No, there were only like three full season drivers.

51:05.980 --> 51:06.840
Oh, okay.

51:06.840 --> 51:07.420
Never mind.

51:07.420 --> 51:07.840
Nice.

51:07.840 --> 51:08.740
How is that?

51:08.740 --> 51:11.360
How are there only like three full season drivers?

51:11.360 --> 51:13.260
And Barrichello still came third.

51:13.260 --> 51:14.400
Oh my goodness.

51:14.400 --> 51:17.040
This list actually pains me.

51:17.040 --> 51:21.300
Because the fourth guy just missed two whole race weekends.

51:21.300 --> 51:21.920
Oh?

51:22.080 --> 51:24.640
Which is like hard to say if he did like whole season.

51:24.640 --> 51:27.980
The fifth guy missed also two whole race weekends.

51:27.980 --> 51:31.960
And everyone below just did like just one or two race weekends.

51:31.960 --> 51:36.060
Except for the guy who withdrawed from like all of the races.

51:36.060 --> 51:36.740
Huh?

51:37.200 --> 51:38.820
But I don't count at full season.

51:38.820 --> 51:40.660
I mean, he has so much experience.

51:40.660 --> 51:41.200
He can be.

51:41.200 --> 51:43.060
He's even in an F2 season.

51:43.060 --> 51:49.780
But on the bright side, Yevan David was a guest driver and thus unable to receive points.

51:49.780 --> 51:51.980
But he did really well, actually.

51:51.980 --> 51:54.620
He came first, third and first.

51:54.620 --> 51:56.520
Which is pretty good.

51:56.520 --> 51:57.740
Which is pretty good, I say.

51:57.740 --> 52:02.060
I mean, you only have to drive against like three drivers who are apparently kind of a**.

52:02.060 --> 52:03.160
Yeah, yeah.

52:03.160 --> 52:04.840
Let's see how they do.

52:04.840 --> 52:07.940
I miss PHM.

52:07.940 --> 52:12.660
You know, I took over from PHM and they were also kind of a**.

52:12.660 --> 52:15.860
But at least they were, you know, they weren't money laundering.

